{"id":"physics/0407008","submitter":"Iver. H. Brevik","authors":"Jean-Pierre Delville, Alexis Casner, Regis Wunenburger, and Iver\n  Brevik","title":"Optical Deformability of Fluid Interfaces","comments":"75 pages, 38 figures. To appear in the volume \"Focus on Lasers and\n  Electro-Optics Research\", ed. Nova Science Publications","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.optics","license":null,"abstract":"  The formation, deformation, and break-up of liquid interfaces are ubiquitous\nphenomena in nature. In the present article we discuss the deformation of a\nliquid interface produced by optical radiation forces. Usually, the bending of\nsuch an interface by the radiation pressure of a c.w. laser beam is weak.\nHowever, the effect can be enhanced significantly if one works with a\nnear-critical phase-separated liquid mixture, whereby the surface tension\nbecomes weak. The bending may in this way become as large as several tenths of\nmicrometers, even with the use of only moderate laser power. This\nnear-criticality is a key element in our experimental investigations as\nreviewed in the article. The effect is achieved by working with a micellar\nphase of microemulsions, at room temperature. We give a brief survey of the\ntheory of electromagnetic forces on continuous matter, and survey earlier\nexperiments in this area, such as the Ashkin-Dziedzic optical radiation force\nexperiment on a water/air surface (1973), the Zhang-Chang experiment on the\nlaser-induced deformation of a micrometer-sized spherical water droplet (1988),\nand the experiment of Sakai et al. measuring surface tensions of interfaces in\na non-contact manner (2001). Thereafter, we survey results we obtained in\nrecent years by performing experiments on near-critical interfaces, such as\ninterface bending in the linear regime, stationary large deformations of liquid\ninterfaces, asymmetric pressure effects on interfaces under intense\nillumination, nonlinear deformations, and laser-sustained liquid columns.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 1 Jul 2004 18:29:21 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
